result.execSummary:
The defendant Reynaldo Hinojosa was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • 4th Degree Sexual Assault, a class A misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 940.225(3m).

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

records.addlTxt: 11:32 am case called. Defendant Reynaldo  Hinojosa in court with attorney Erik C. Johnson.  Steven Paul Anderson appeared for the State of Wisconsin. Statement by victim to the court. No statement by defendant. Court sentences the defendant to: 60 days WCJ, with Huber and Good Time Credit. Credit for 3 days time served. To begin no later than November 16, 2018. Court does not object to jail transfer and does not object to out of county travel for work purposes. Costs to be paid out of bond posted.  Court declines to order Sex Offender registry under 301.45. DNA Sample and Surcharge ordered by the Court.  Defendant advised of right to expunge DNA record through the Department of Justice. Appeal Rights Given.

2:07 pm case called. Defendant Reynaldo  Hinojosa in court with attorney Erik C. Johnson.  Steven Paul Anderson appeared for the State of Wisconsin. Court goes over motion filed by Attorney Johnson. Statement by Court regarding motion. Statement between court and counsel regarding motion. Court makes statement regarding request and grants motion made by Attorney Johnson-a prima facia record has been made for some records but not all. Court determines the following documents are to be provided to the court for in-camera inspection-Court directs that J.D.S. be informed of in-camera insepection of records of Jefferson County Department of Human Services from 1/1/15 to present and the records of the Jefferson County Sheriff's Department (Not subject to Shiffra or Green confidentiality).  Court also orders any health care records from Mead Medical and Women's Health Center in Watertown are also subject to the in-camera inspection. J.D.S. has a right to decline permission being authorized and an authorization being issued for the in-camera inspection. After the records are provided to the court in-camera.If the court determines there are records to be released there will be an additional notification to the victim regarding release-at which time the victim may decline release. Were the victim to decline to disclose the records the court would enter an order prohibitting her from testifying in this matter. Court directs that the records from Dodgeland  & Watertown High school-records relating to staff, counselors, or conventional guidance records be produced for in-camera inspection. Records ordered to be produced are January 1, 2015 to the present. Court directs records from Aurora Medical center from December 1, 2015 to present are made subject to this order, along with records from Waushara Family Physicians, Waushara County Human Services, and records from Wautoma High School-records memorializing the incident as disclosed. Court declines to order Washington County Health Center or WMHI records be produced. Court offers to counsel traveling to the places where these records are available. Court requests Attorney Johnson to draft order. Court orders the documents be produced by November 1, 2016.  Status conference scheduled for November 29, 2016 at 10:00 am.

Case Called @ 10:05 AM: Defendant Reynaldo Hinojosa in court with attorney Ben Szilagyi, both appearing via video.  Defendant Reynaldo Hinojosa in custody.  Steven Paul Anderson appeared for the State of Wisconsin.    Complaint Stated - Advised of offense and minimum/maximum penalty.  Receipt Admitted - Reading Waived.  Per SPD:  Def's eligibility will depend on custody status.  ADA argues as to cash bond of $1000-2000.00 based  upon allegations.  Based upon the complaint, SPD would move for dismissal of the complaint as filed - does not meet the 4 Corners requirement.  The Court:  Noting concerns raised by SPD and specifically refers to Para 7 of the Complaint which supports PC finding and supports requirement of bond.  Orders $1500 cash bond w/conditions.  SPD requests prelim scheduling.  Pre-Lim Scheduled - NOH Given. Court enters Riverside Ruling in favor of the State and probable cause finding as to each count alleged within the complaint.
